[13:34:53    65] -Completed:
[13:34:53    65] -- Parser input is slice-backed: `parse_buffer.content: &[c_uchar]` with safe access helpers.
[13:34:53    65] -- Parser value functions use `&mut cJSON` for parsed nodes: `parse_number`, `parse_string`, `parse_value`, `parse_array`, and `parse_object`.
[13:34:53    65] -- `parse_number` uses safe Rust parsing instead of hook-allocated scratch memory, `memcpy`, `strtod`, and locale FFI.
[13:34:53    65] -- `cJSON_New_Item` returns `Option<&'static mut cJSON>` while preserving hook allocator behavior. It initializes allocated memory via `MaybeUninit::write`; do not change this to assigning through an uninitialized `&mut cJSON`.
[13:34:53    65] -- Parser allocation call sites, `cJSON_ParseWithLengthOpts`, `create_reference`, simple `cJSON_Create*` constructors, and the first allocation in `cJSON_Duplicate_rec` use the reference-returning allocator.
[13:34:53    65] -- `parse_array` and `parse_object` now build child lists without unsafe raw-pointer dereferences.
[13:34:53    65] -- `cJSON_CreateIntArray`, `cJSON_CreateFloatArray`, `cJSON_CreateDoubleArray`, and `cJSON_CreateStringArray` now take safe slices in implementation functions. Their exported wrappers keep the C ABI and convert raw input arrays.
[13:34:53    65] -- Simple constructors and reference constructors are safe implementation functions. Exported wrappers keep the C ABI.
[13:34:53    65] -- `cJSON_AddStringToObject` and `cJSON_AddRawToObject` accept `Option<&CStr>` for value strings. Exported wrappers convert raw pointers.
[13:34:53    65] -- `cJSON_strdup` takes `Option<&CStr>` and copies `to_bytes_with_nul()` through a Rust slice. It still returns hook-allocated raw storage.
[13:34:53    65] -- `add_item_to_object`, `cJSON_InsertItemInArray`, `cJSON_DetachItemViaPointer`, and `cJSON_ReplaceItemViaPointer` use safe `Option<&mut cJSON>` parent boundaries for implementation callers while item/replacement pointers remain raw pending ownership work.
[13:34:53    65] -- `get_array_item`, `cJSON_GetArraySize`, and `cJSON_GetArrayItem` use `Option<&cJSON>` implementation APIs.
[13:34:53    65] -- `create_reference` takes `Option<&cJSON>` and copies the node with Rust `Copy` assignment instead of `memcpy`.
[13:34:53    65] -- `get_object_item` now takes `Option<&cJSON>` and `Option<&CStr>` and returns `Option<&cJSON>`. The public implementation APIs `cJSON_GetObjectItem`, `cJSON_GetObjectItemCaseSensitive`, and `cJSON_HasObjectItem` are safe; exported wrappers preserve the C ABI.
[13:34:53    65] -- Object detach/delete implementation functions accept safe object/key options, object replacement uses the safe lookup helper, and `cJSON_Compare` object matching no longer calls a raw-pointer lookup or dereferences the matched item pointer.
[13:34:53    65] -- `cJSON_DetachItemFromArray`, `cJSON_DeleteItemFromArray`, `cJSON_ReplaceItemInArray`, and `cJSON_InsertItemInArray` now take `Option<&mut cJSON>` for the array in implementation code. Exported wrappers keep raw C ABI signatures and convert with `as_mut()`.
[13:34:53    65] -- `cJSON_DetachItemViaPointer` and `cJSON_ReplaceItemViaPointer` now take `Option<&mut cJSON>` for the parent in implementation code. Their exported wrappers keep raw C ABI signatures and convert with `as_mut()`. This removed unsafe calls from array/object detach and replace callers.
[13:34:53    65] -- `replace_item_in_object` now takes `Option<&mut cJSON>` for the object and `Option<&CStr>` for the key, and `cJSON_ReplaceItemInObject` / `cJSON_ReplaceItemInObjectCaseSensitive` are safe implementation functions. Exported wrappers keep raw C ABI signatures and convert with `as_mut()` / `CStr::from_ptr()`. The helper intentionally still rewrites the replacement key before discovering a null/missing object, matching the previous behavior.
